  "texts": [
    "To better understand this methodological diversity, it is important to systematically compare the main categories of AI techniques applied in this context.",
    "The three most common types are traditional machine learning methods, deep learning models, and hybrid or multimodal systems.",
    "Each of these categories contributes distinct strengths and faces specific limitations when applied to sensory research.",
    "Literature Main focus Brief description Key issues addressed Outcome Ritsch et al. (2024) Obesity, Gastric Modulation Investigates the influence of gastric innervation and mechanical function on food reward, olfaction, and taste in individuals with obesity or those who have undergone bariatric surgery Understanding sensory perception changes post-surgery Framework for future research into sensory modulation in obesity Sukaew (2024) Aroma, Flavor Innovation Examines trends in flavor and aroma research, highlighting the shift to synthetic chemicals in response to increased demand and consumer health-focused products in the food industry Challenges in traditional flavor extraction methods Insights into future directions for sustainable flavor production Callejon-Leblic et al.",
    "(2021) Predictive Modeling, Sensory Loss Proposes a machine learning framework to predict and analyze taste and smell loss using advanced algorithms, achieving high accuracy Correlation of sensory loss with health indicators Demonstrates the diagnostic potential of sensory analysis Fekri Azgomi et al. (2023) Cognitive States, Wearable Tech Studies the effects of auditory, gustatory, and olfactory stimulation on cognitive arousal, using wearable technologies to regulate performance states of participants Need for effective cognitive state regulation methods Advances towards personalized cognitive enhancement technologies Zheng et al."
  ]
